# Markdown Formatting Standards

When generating markdown content, strictly follow these formatting rules to ensure compliance with `.markdownlint.yaml`:

## Headers
- Use ATX style headers with `#` symbols
- Maximum line length: 120 characters
- No trailing punctuation in headers
- Allow duplicate headings only in different sections

## Lists
- Use dash (`-`) for unordered lists
- Use ordered numbers for ordered lists
- Indent list items with exactly 2 spaces
- Allow multiple spaces after list markers

## Code and Technical Content
- Use fenced code blocks with triple backticks
- Maximum code block line length: 120 characters
- Allow inline HTML when needed for complex formatting
- Allow bare URLs in technical documentation

## Line Length and Spacing
- Maximum line length: 120 characters for all content
- Allow 2 trailing spaces for line breaks
- No trailing spaces otherwise

## Special Cases
- Allow emphasis used instead of headers when appropriate
- Allow first line to not be a top-level header
- Allow inline HTML for complex tables and formatting

## Content Generation Guidelines

### Documentation Structure
- Start with clear, descriptive headers
- Use consistent hierarchy (H1 -> H2 -> H3)
- Include table of contents for long documents
- Add descriptive alt text for any images

### Technical Documentation
- Use code blocks for commands, configuration, and code
- Include language hints for syntax highlighting
- Use inline code for file paths, commands, and variables
- Create clear, actionable task lists

### Lists and Task Items
- Use consistent checkbox format: `- [ ]` for tasks
- Use `- [x]` for completed tasks
- Maintain proper indentation (2 spaces)
- Group related items under descriptive headers

### Tables and Data
- Use HTML tables for complex data when needed
- Ensure proper alignment and formatting
- Include headers for all columns
- Keep tables within line length limits

## Validation Checklist

Before finalizing any markdown content, verify:
- [ ] All headers use ATX style (`#`)
- [ ] Lists use dash (`-`) for unordered items
- [ ] Proper 2-space indentation throughout
- [ ] No lines exceed 120 characters
- [ ] Code blocks are properly fenced
- [ ] No trailing spaces (except 2 for line breaks)
- [ ] Consistent formatting and structure

## Examples

### Correct Header Format
```markdown
# Main Header
## Sub Header
### Section Header
```

### Correct List Format
```markdown
- [ ] Task item
- [x] Completed task
  - [ ] Sub-task with proper indentation
```

### Correct Code Block
```markdown
```bash
# Example command
sudo apt update
```
```

### Correct Table Format
```markdown
| Column 1 | Column 2 |
|----------|----------|
| Data 1   | Data 2   |
```

## Error Prevention

- Always test generated content against markdownlint
- Use consistent formatting patterns
- Maintain readability and clarity
- Follow established documentation conventions
